    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_948450006" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/948450006" />
    <a title="Smiley " class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/2580971-smiley"><img alt="Smiley " src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1525349534p2/2580971.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/948450006?book_show_action=true">May 26, 2014</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Smiley " class="user" itemprop="url" name="Smiley " href="/user/show/2580971-smiley">Smiley </a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Hardcover 9784805311080" href="/book/show/8980058-the-pillow-book-of-sei-shonagon">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/2580971-smiley?shelf=japan">japan</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/2580971-smiley?shelf=journal">journal</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer948450006" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer16488400921102799291">I preferred this memoir-like book less than its contemporary one &quot;The Gossamer Years&quot; (Tuttle, 1964) translated by Edward Seidensticker. Translated by Arthur Waley, one of the great Orientalists, its recorded episodes have been fragmentary, presumably newly compiled under headings for more ease in reading as well as following the author‚Äôs train of thought.<br/><br/>This information related to ‚ÄúThe Gossamer Years‚Äù, I think, should throw more light on our understanding:<br/>Very little is known of the author out</span>
  <span id="freeText16488400921102799291" style="display:none">I preferred this memoir-like book less than its contemporary one "The Gossamer Years" (Tuttle, 1964) translated by Edward Seidensticker. Translated by Arthur Waley, one of the great Orientalists, its recorded episodes have been fragmentary, presumably newly compiled under headings for more ease in reading as well as following the author‚Äôs train of thought.<br /><br />This information related to ‚ÄúThe Gossamer Years‚Äù, I think, should throw more light on our understanding:<br />Very little is known of the author outside of what is related in her diary. Her name is unknown ‚Äì but she was related to the Lady Murasaki, author of The Tale of Genji, and to Sei Shonagon, author of The Pillow Book. (Goodreads)<br /><br />Moreover, from the forward by Dennis Washburn, we know that this book presents ‚Äúa vivid narrative voice in essays that present her views on many different topics dealing with proper etiquette, literary taste, or the ideal courtier.‚Äù (p. 17) Even though we can find another full-length English translations by Ivan Morris and Meredith McKinney, we should read this one since ‚Äú ‚Ä¶, Waley continues to be revered and his work still read, and deservedly so ‚Äì not simply because of his historical importance ‚Ä¶, but because the beauty of his prose captures the artistic spirit of a brilliant and fascinating woman of Heian Japan.‚Äù (p. 19)<br /><br />However, having recently read its translation by Dr Ivan Morris in the same title (Penguin, 1981), I found this book has notably been supplemented by Dr Arthur Waley‚Äôs remarks followed by his translated texts, in other words, we would read his added explanatory lines then his translation deemed appropriate from the original Japanese book. Thus, its opening paragraph on page 23 and its subsequent 47.5 pages should be read as a lengthy introduction till we find the first topic, MASAHIRO. To allow my readers to be familiar with his style from its first paragraph extracted, the first topics are presented for you to try.<br /><br />MASAHIRO<br />Everyone laughs at Masahiro. It must really be very painful for his parents and friends. If he is seen anywhere with at all a decent-looking servant in attendance upon him, someone is sure to send for the fellow and ask him whether he can be in his senses, to wait upon such a master. Everything at his house is extremely well done and he chooses his clothes with unusually good taste; but the only result is to make people say: ‚ÄúHow nice those things would look on anyone else!‚Äù <br />‚Ä¶ (p. 71)<br /><br />ANNOYING THINGS<br />When one sends a poem or a kayeshi (‚Äúreturn-poem‚Äù) to someone and, after it has gone, thinks of some small alteration ‚Äì perhaps only a couple of letters ‚Äì that would have improved it. <br />‚Ä¶ (p. 76)<br /><br />VERY TIRESOME THINGS<br />When a poem of one‚Äôs own, that one has allowed someone else to use as his, is singled out for praise.<br />‚Ä¶ (p. 81)<br />etc.<br /><br />Furthermore, these are the following topics in which you may read as you like. <br /><br />MISCELLANEOUS<br />NARINOBU<br />THE STORM<br />PILGRIMAGE TO THE HASEDERA<br />STRAY NOTES<br />PRETTY THINGS<br />CHILDREN<br />THINGS THAT GIVE ME AN UNCOMFROTABLE FEELING<br />TOOTHACHE<br />ILLNESS</span>
  <a data-text-id="16488400921102799291" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


