    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1627687762" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1627687762" />
    <a title="shanghao" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/8606081-shanghao"><img alt="shanghao" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1619773023p2/8606081.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1627687762?book_show_action=true">May 03, 2016</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="shanghao" class="user" itemprop="url" name="shanghao" href="/user/show/8606081-shanghao">shanghao</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/8606081-shanghao?shelf=society">society</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/8606081-shanghao?shelf=shorts">shorts</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/8606081-shanghao?shelf=orient">orient</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/8606081-shanghao?shelf=ye-olde-days">ye-olde-days</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1627687762" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer14301312533440206162"><b>Beautiful Things</b><br/>Flashes of wit, impunity, tenderness. Contradictions and multiple facets of Sei&apos;s character. Unabashed honesty, pettiness and surprising piety. <br/><br/><b>Annoying Things</b><br/>Intrusions to the actual entries from the translator, which usually ended as abruptly as they started. <br/><br/>The explanations were helpful, but the inconsistent way in which things were explained (some via footnotes, some directly slipped between the paragraphs) can be confusing. Definitely affected my enjoyment of reading this, </span>
  <span id="freeText14301312533440206162" style="display:none"><b>Beautiful Things</b><br />Flashes of wit, impunity, tenderness. Contradictions and multiple facets of Sei's character. Unabashed honesty, pettiness and surprising piety. <br /><br /><b>Annoying Things</b><br />Intrusions to the actual entries from the translator, which usually ended as abruptly as they started. <br /><br />The explanations were helpful, but the inconsistent way in which things were explained (some via footnotes, some directly slipped between the paragraphs) can be confusing. Definitely affected my enjoyment of reading this, therefore the 2 stars. I'm inclined to rate the content 4 stars actually.<br /><br /><b>Things to Ponder</b><br />How the most famous literature of this era had come from women rather than men, as opposed to China. Apparently this was attributed to the men usually trying to emulate the great Chinese poets, whereas the women were less restrained by norms and as a result produced more authentic, lasting works.<br /><br /><b>The Value of Triviality</b><br />Sei Shonagon fussed over the most trivial things, and perhaps she could be seen as shallow and aloof to the greater issues of the world. Hers might only have been a reflection of idyllic court life, and there might have been real suffering beyond the palace. <br /><br />Yet, I felt that what she's experiencing and her 'first-world complaints', so to speak, are bygone rarities that we in this current shambolic era do not have the luxury to express as nonchalantly as she did. <br /><br />We should be so lucky when our most pressing concerns consist of pretending to be asleep, to no avail, when someone you're not in the mood of seeing come a-knocking in the wee small hours of the morning, the nerve! <br /><br />Frankly I'm not sure which is better, living in trying times but developing a more wordly and magnanimous heart, with many suffering the consequences of dire decisions; or in an idyllic one where one is more self-centred, but the general populace happier on the whole in a simpler, small-minded world if you will. <br /><br />Well if anything, change will come. As Sei Shonagon's trivial but relatively peaceful era had passed, so will our erratic, exciting(?) one give way. <br /><br />When change does sweep through our current times, may it be for peace and joy. (gosh I sound like a beauty pageant contestant. But really.) I sure hope the complaints in my no-holds-barred pillow book would only be trivial, petty ones - not because I'm shallow (though I am a lot of the time ^^), but because it's afforded by a life and world well worth living.</span>
  <a data-text-id="14301312533440206162" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


